  "content": {
    "statement": {
      "text": "Atoms consist of a dense, positively charged nucleus surrounded by negatively charged electrons in quantum mechanical orbitals. The characteristic atomic scale is set by the Bohr radius (a_0 ≈ 5.29 × 10^-11 m), which is about 10^25 times larger than the Planck length.",
      "formal": "a_0 = ℏ/(m_e c α) = 4πε_0ℏ²/(m_e e²) ≈ 5.29 × 10^-11 m"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "intuition": "An atom is like a miniature solar system, but governed by quantum mechanics rather than gravity. The electrons don't orbit in fixed paths but exist in probability clouds (orbitals) around the nucleus. The size of these orbitals is determined by fundamental constants.",
      "key_insight": "The atomic scale emerges from the competition between electromagnetic attraction (which would collapse the electron onto the nucleus) and quantum mechanical kinetic energy (which resists localization). The balance occurs at the Bohr radius.",
      "scale_hierarchy": {
        "atomic_radius": "~10^-10 m",
        "nuclear_radius": "~10^-15 m",
        "planck_length": "~10^-35 m",
        "ratio_atomic_to_planck": "~10^25"
      }
    },
